  "created": "2025-10-15",
  "description": "Transcription termination in E. coli occurs through two major mechanisms: intrinsic (Rho-independent) and Rho-dependent termination. Intrinsic termination relies on formation of a stable RNA hairpin followed by a U-rich tract, causing RNAP to pause and dissociate. The hairpin structure destabilizes the RNA-DNA hybrid, allowing transcript release. Rho-dependent termination requires the Rho hexameric helicase, which binds to rut (Rho utilization) sites on nascent RNA, translocates 5' to 3' in an ATP-dependent manner, catches up to paused RNAP, and actively dissociates the elongation complex. Both mechanisms ensure proper transcript 3' end formation and RNAP recycling. This flowchart illustrates both termination pathways, the structural features that trigger each mechanism, and the molecular events leading to transcript release and polymerase dissociation.",
  "id": "ecoli_transcription_termination",
